description.value: Egyptian terracotta mould fragment. An upper part broken from the front mould for a man, standing with his arms to his sides: he is lost from the waist down. He has a bald head and thickened lips, the lower one rather twisted as well as a broken nose. Although he does not wear a topknot, he seems to be a boxer, as what are probably the upper thongs of a sphaira or caestus (a boxing-glove) appear on the impression’s left arm; the right arm also has a tiny area that may be part of such a thong. Probably part of a two-piece set of moulds. Brown Nile silt with a thick grey core, common fine gold mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Terracotta front-mould and white plaster cast for a group featuring the Egyptian Hermes seated, writing on a papyrus scroll lying across his knees. He wears only a chlamys over his shoulders, fastened by a brooch. There are wings in his hair and a diadem holds a lotus petal at its centre. His hair is curly and he has sideburns in front of his ears. Hermes is flanked by two monkeys. That on his right stands with his arms bent by his sides, and wears a hooded cloak; his phallus is very long. The monkey on Hermes' left side sits on a stool or chest, reading a papyrus scroll on his lap, held open by both hands. He wears a necklace with three large pendants; by his side is a purse or a small jar. There are two registration hollows, one on each side, low down.

description.value: A terracotta front-mould fragment for a standing female saint or beneficent demon, the head and one shoulder only surviving. She has a large parabolic wreath, with a cabled band surmounted by a small circle, and radiating lines on the edges; a small circle on the brow. There are two choker necklets and part of a boss of a further necklace. A mark below the ear indicates where these figures normally have a piercing from front to rear. It has a plain rounded back. Pink Aswan kaolinite clay, with some mica.

description.value: The upper part of a plaster front-mould for a terracotta figure of a draped man, probably a dancer or other entertainer, broken off at the top of the thighs. He has a full head of curly hair and wears a twisted necklet or torc; he may be a black African or a Gaul. He wears a tunic, perhaps with short sleeves; it is rolled up to expose his genitals. His right arm (in the impression) is bent with the forearm stretched out sideways, and his left arm is fully bent, the forearm raised and the hand extended with the palm uppermost. Three registration hollows survive, one each side of the head and one above the head. White plaster; traces of an orange-red paint on the edges and in the registration hollows.
